item.title: Spoiler: US Tech companies are no longer trustworthy
item.description:
https://www.zdnet.com/article/france-dumps-teams-zoom-homegrown-videoconferencing-eu-digital-sovereignty/
FTA: As David Amiel, France's minister-delegate for the civil service and state reform, put it: France is committed "to regaining our digital independence. We cannot risk having our scientific exchanges, our sensitive data, and our strategic innovations exposed to non-European actors." So, France is pushing US tech giants out of the French government. They're moving civil servants off Microsoft Teams and Zoom and onto a homegrown videoconferencing platform called Visio -- all in the name of sovereign control over its digital infrastructure. Paris has framed the decision as a strategic break from dependence on American cloud and collaboration platforms. The French government is explicitly linking it to a broader doctrine of "digital sovereignty." This EU-based movement, which has been around for over a decade, is dedicated to the proposition that EU countries should rely on native EU tech companies, cloud services, and platforms.

item.title: RIP Paisley
item.description:
I took in kittens Paisley and Pongo a couple of weeks ago, but after two days, I took them back to the humane society because they stopped eating. Jess has done absolutely everything in her power to save them, but Paisley just couldn’t recover. She had to be euthanized this morning.
Jess sent me this pic as they were headed to the vet. She was syringe feeding Paisley every few hours, plus giving fluids twice a day, and she was showering her with love and pets and cuddles. There was nothing else we could have done. Fading Kitten Syndrome is a cruel bastard
Luckily her big brother Pongo is thriving. He’s up to 2.5 pounds, so they’re gonna keep an eye on him for a week (to be sure he doesn’t have the same kind of thing that Paisley had), and then they’ll neuter him and put him up for adoption. The Humane Society does AMAZING work with their animals. I offered to post their wishlist, in case anyone out there wants to help them out. https://www.amazon.com/hz/wishlist/ls/KZBC3EH8YK4J?ref_=wl_share
RIP, baby girl. I only had you for a few short days but you touched my heart and will never be forgotten.

I can't speak for others but I make games because I remember that feeling when you were a kid and how much fun it was to sit there and play with your brothers or you friends from school and just have these unforgettable moments that you would discuss even months later like you went on an adventure. I would love to have one of my games make someone younger now have the same experiences. Obviously it would be nice to make money, but the reality is that my first game didn't. I didn't stop and my second game didn't too, but the reactions I've gotten were so heartwarming that I just don't want to stop because games haven't sold well.
